<subSubSection id="C33B07F8072AA23153D2EF18FCA5472D" lastPageId="2" lastPageNumber="287" pageId="1" pageNumber="286" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="8B9E5473072AA23253D2EF18FCB748EC" blockId="1.[136,1452,1627,2086]" pageId="1" pageNumber="286">
<emphasis id="B9558861072AA23253D2EF18FFF54947" bold="true" box="[136,212,1628,1654]" pageId="1" pageNumber="286">Notes:</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation id="EFB02982072AA2325385EF18FE4A4947" author="Nees Von Esenbeck, C. G." box="[223,363,1628,1654]" pageId="1" pageNumber="286" pagination="91 - 93" refId="ref3929" refString="Nees Von Esenbeck, C. G. (1832) Acanthaceae Indiae Orientalis. In: N. Wallich (Ed.) Plantae Asiaticae rariores, or, Descriptions and figures of a select number of unpublished East Indian plants, 3. Treuttel et Wurtz, London, pp. 91 - 93." type="book chapter" year="1832">Nees (1832)</bibRefCitation>
validated 
<taxonomicName id="4C212FF0072AA23252BDEF1FFD9C4944" authorityName="Heyne ex Nees" authorityYear="1832" box="[487,701,1627,1653]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Acanthaceae" genus="Barleria" kingdom="Plantae" order="Lamiales" pageId="1" pageNumber="286" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="cuspidata">
<emphasis id="B9558861072AA23252BDEF1FFD9C4944" box="[487,701,1627,1653]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="286">Barleria cuspidata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
based on three gatherings listed under this name (“Herb. Madr., Herb. Heyn. 
<emphasis id="B9558861072AA2325244EFC4FE1349A8" box="[286,306,1664,1689]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="286">et</emphasis>
Herb. Wight. Wall. Cat. n. 2499a, b, c”) in Wallich’s Catalogue (1830a: 75), one distributed as ‘ 
<taxonomicName id="4C212FF0072AA23256C9EFC4FE21498C" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Acanthaceae" genus="Barleria" kingdom="Plantae" order="Lamiales" pageId="1" pageNumber="286" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="mucronata">
<emphasis id="B9558861072AA23256C9EFC4FE21498C" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="286">B. mucronata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
’ from Wight’s herbarium (“Wight Herb. propr. n. 16”), and another as “ 
<taxonomicName id="4C212FF0072AA2325716EFE0FA40498F" authority="Hb. Heyn." authorityName="Hb. Heyn." box="[1100,1377,1699,1726]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Acanthaceae" genus="Barleria" kingdom="Plantae" order="Lamiales" pageId="1" pageNumber="286" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="noctiflora">
<emphasis id="B9558861072AA2325716EFE0FBFC498C" box="[1100,1245,1699,1725]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="286">B. noctiflora</emphasis>
Hb. Heyn.
</taxonomicName>
” from Wallich’s Catalogue (“n. 2496c”). Nees also indicated two localities: “in aridis Indiae or., prope Tanschaur (Tanjore), (Linn.)” and “In collibus provinciae Madurae, Dindygul etc. (Wight)”. The first appears to be a reference to what is cited (“aridis Tanschaur. König”) in the protologue of 
<taxonomicName id="4C212FF0072AA2325042EE54FC894818" box="[792,936,1807,1833]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Acanthaceae" genus="Barleria" kingdom="Plantae" order="Lamiales" pageId="1" pageNumber="286" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="noctiflora">
<emphasis id="B9558861072AA2325042EE54FC894818" box="[792,936,1807,1833]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="286">B. noctiflora</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
L.f. (1782: 290), which 
<bibRefCitation id="EFB02982072AA2325793EE54FA74481B" author="Nees Von Esenbeck, C. G." box="[1225,1365,1808,1834]" pageId="1" pageNumber="286" pagination="91 - 93" refId="ref3929" refString="Nees Von Esenbeck, C. G. (1832) Acanthaceae Indiae Orientalis. In: N. Wallich (Ed.) Plantae Asiaticae rariores, or, Descriptions and figures of a select number of unpublished East Indian plants, 3. Treuttel et Wurtz, London, pp. 91 - 93." type="book chapter" year="1832">Nees (1832)</bibRefCitation>
treated as a distinct species without citing this locality, so it is unclear to what Nees may have been referring. None of the specimens involved was indicated as a type. Therefore, the specimens 2499a, b and c and the other 
<specimenCount id="9D279FFA072AA232565EEE1CFA8D4840" box="[1284,1452,1879,1906]" pageId="1" pageNumber="286" type="generic">two specimens</specimenCount>
constitute 
<typeStatus id="549AEAD1072AA23253A7EE38FE4248A7" box="[253,355,1916,1942]" pageId="1" pageNumber="286">syntypes</typeStatus>
. 
<bibRefCitation id="EFB02982072AA2325234EE3FFDF048A7" author="Shendage, S. M. &amp; Yadav, S. R." box="[366,721,1915,1942]" pageId="1" pageNumber="286" pagination="81 - 130" refId="ref4246" refString="Shendage, S. M. &amp; Yadav, S. R. (2010) Revision of the genus Barleria (Acanthaceae) in India. Rheedea 20: 81 - 130." type="journal article" year="2010">Shendage &amp; Yadav (2010: 111)</bibRefCitation>
indicated “Wall., Numer. List No. 2499 (Photo!, K)” as “Type”, but this is not a single gathering (Art. 9.17 of the ICN) nor did they use the term “here designated” (Art. 7.11 of the ICN) or an equivalent, so this was not an acceptable lectotypification.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8B9E5473072AA23153E7EEACFDB24E79" blockId="1.[136,1452,1627,2086]" lastBlockId="2.[136,1452,158,329]" lastPageId="2" lastPageNumber="287" pageId="1" pageNumber="286">
While searching for the relevant 
<typeStatus id="549AEAD1072AA232516DEEACFD464733" box="[567,615,2024,2050]" pageId="1" pageNumber="286">type</typeStatus>
we found several sheets associated with 
<taxonomicName id="4C212FF0072AA232571BEEA3FA374730" authorityName="Heyne ex Nees" authorityYear="1832" box="[1089,1302,2023,2049]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Acanthaceae" genus="Barleria" kingdom="Plantae" order="Lamiales" pageId="1" pageNumber="286" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="cuspidata">
<emphasis id="B9558861072AA232571BEEA3FA374730" box="[1089,1302,2023,2049]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="286">Barleria cuspidata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. At the Graz herbarium (GZU), where Nees’s 
<taxonomicName id="4C212FF0072AA2325159E14FFDB34714" box="[515,658,2059,2085]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Acanthaceae" kingdom="Plantae" order="Lamiales" pageId="1" pageNumber="286" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="family">Acanthaceae</taxonomicName>
specimens now reside (
<bibRefCitation id="EFB02982072AA23250F3E14FFBD54717" author="Stafleu, F. A. &amp; Cowan, R. S." box="[937,1268,2059,2086]" pageId="1" pageNumber="286" refId="ref4280" refString="Stafleu, F. A. &amp; Cowan, R. S. (1981) Taxonomic literature, ed. 2. A selective guide to botanical publications and collections with dates, commentaries and types. Vol. III: Lh-O. Utrecht: Bohn, Scheltema &amp; Holkema, pp. 706." type="book" year="1981">Stafleu &amp; Cowan 1981: 706</bibRefCitation>
), we found five sheets, viz. 2499a (GZU000251701) annotated with ‘Herb. Madr.’, 2499b (GZU000251699) with ‘Herb. Heyn.’, 2499c (GZU000251537) with ‘Herb. Wight.’, 2496c (GZU000251698) with ‘ 
<taxonomicName id="4C212FF00729A23150F4E986FA304FEC" authority="Herb. Heyn" authorityName="Herb. Heyn" box="[942,1297,194,221]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Acanthaceae" genus="Barleria" kingdom="Plantae" order="Lamiales" pageId="2" pageNumber="287" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="noctiflora">
<emphasis id="B95588610729A23150F4E986FBA54FED" box="[942,1156,194,220]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="287">Barleria noctiflora</emphasis>
Herb. Heyn
</taxonomicName>
/ ad partem’, and Herb. Wight propr. 16 (GZU000249396) with “ 
<taxonomicName id="4C212FF00729A23151BBE9A2FCE04E31" box="[737,961,230,256]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Acanthaceae" genus="Barleria" kingdom="Plantae" order="Lamiales" pageId="2" pageNumber="287" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="mucronata">
<emphasis id="B95588610729A23151BBE9A2FCE04E31" box="[737,961,230,256]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="287">Barleria mucronata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
”. The specimen number 16 distributed by Wight, according to 
<bibRefCitation id="EFB029820729A2315234E84EFDB04E15" author="Wight, R. &amp; Arnott, G. A. W." box="[366,657,266,292]" pageId="2" pageNumber="287" refId="ref4561" refString="Wight, R. &amp; Arnott, G. A. W. (1934) Prodromus florae peninsula Indiae orientalis. Parbury, Allen, &amp; Co., London, pp. 4." type="book" year="1934">Wight &amp; Arnott (1934: 4)</bibRefCitation>
, was actually a species of 
<taxonomicName id="4C212FF00729A23150E6E84EFB614E15" box="[956,1088,266,292]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Ranunculaceae" genus="Ranunculus" kingdom="Plantae" order="Ranunculales" pageId="2" pageNumber="287" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B95588610729A23150E6E84EFB614E15" box="[956,1088,266,292]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="287">Ranunculus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, prompting 
<bibRefCitation id="EFB029820729A2315791E84FFAAF4E15" author="Nees Von Esenbeck, C. G." box="[1227,1422,266,293]" pageId="2" pageNumber="287" pagination="46 - 519" refId="ref3986" refString="Nees Von Esenbeck, C. G. (1847) Acanthaceae. In: de Candolle, A. L. P. P. (Ed.) Prodromus Systematis Naturalis Regni Vegetabilis 11. Masson, Paris, pp. 46 - 519." type="journal article" year="1847">Nees (1847: 239)</bibRefCitation>
to later indicate this as “Wight h. propr. n. 1963”.
</paragraph>
<caption id="DF5E04FB0729A23153D2EF3EFE044982" ID-DOI="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6577574" ID-Zenodo-Dep="6577574" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6577574/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="287" startId="2.[136,229,1658,1680]" targetBox="[313,1274,353,1633]" targetPageId="2">
<paragraph id="8B9E54730729A23153D2EF3EFE044982" blockId="2.[136,1452,1658,1716]" pageId="2" pageNumber="287">
<emphasis id="B95588610729A23153D2EF3EFFDC49BE" bold="true" box="[136,253,1658,1680]" pageId="2" pageNumber="287">FIGURE 2.</emphasis>
Lectotype of 
<taxonomicName id="4C212FF00729A23152DBEF3EFD6649BE" box="[385,583,1658,1679]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Acanthaceae" genus="Barleria" kingdom="Plantae" order="Lamiales" pageId="2" pageNumber="287" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="grandiflora">
<emphasis id="B95588610729A23152DBEF3EFD6649BE" box="[385,583,1658,1679]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="287">Barleria grandiflora</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(K001392446) [Reproduced with kind permission of the Board of Trustees, Royal Botanic Gardens, Kew.].
</paragraph>
</caption>
<paragraph id="8B9E54730729A23153E7EFA6FCA5472D" blockId="2.[136,1452,1762,2076]" pageId="2" pageNumber="287">
At the Kew herbarium (K) we found 
<specimenCount id="9D279FFA0729A231513EEFA6FC2349CD" box="[612,770,1762,1788]" pageId="2" pageNumber="287" type="generic">six specimens</specimenCount>
pasted on two sheets (three each on a sheet). The first sheet bears a cut-out label from Wallich’s Catalogue “2499 
<taxonomicName id="4C212FF00729A2315180EE42FB054811" authority="Hb. Madr." authorityName="Hb. Madr." box="[730,1060,1798,1824]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Acanthaceae" genus="Barleria" kingdom="Plantae" order="Lamiales" pageId="2" pageNumber="287" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="cuspidata">
<emphasis id="B95588610729A2315180EE42FC8D4811" box="[730,940,1798,1824]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="287">Barleria cuspidata</emphasis>
Hb. Madr.
</taxonomicName>
/ B. Hb. Heyn. / C. Hb. Wight” and various plant fragments labelled with pencil “a” (K001116219), “b” (K001116217) and “c” (K001116218) whereas the second sheet comprises 
<specimenCount id="9D279FFA0729A231529FEE0AFD5B4859" box="[453,634,1870,1896]" pageId="2" pageNumber="287" type="generic">three specimens</specimenCount>
K000797771, K000797772 and K000797773, of which K000797773 is annotated as ‘2499b / Hb. Heyne’. The specimen K000797771 is annotated ‘Herb. Madr.’ and is without collection number whereas K000797772 bears the label ‘Herb. Wight. propr. 1963’. Five of these specimens, excepting K000797771, appear to be duplicates of specimens Nees possessed in his herbarium and would be original material for his name. From among the original material indicated above we select the specimen 2499b (K000797773) as the 
<typeStatus id="549AEAD10729A23153D2E146FFD3472D" box="[136,242,2050,2076]" pageId="2" pageNumber="287">lectotype</typeStatus>
, it is well preserved and matches well with the protologue.
</paragraph>
